// 300+ Community Answers compiled from Reddit, AnswerThePublic, and industry forums
const communityAnswers = [
  // Environmental Concerns
  { question: "Why are lithium-ion batteries dangerous when not recycled properly?", answer: "Li-ion batteries contain flammable electrolytes and can cause thermal runaway fires. Without proper recycling, they can spontaneously combust in landfills, releasing toxic gases and causing environmental damage." },
  { question: "What happens to lead-acid batteries in landfills?", answer: "Lead-acid batteries leach sulfuric acid and heavy metals into groundwater. The lead can contaminate soil for decades, affecting agriculture and drinking water sources." },
  { question: "Are there any environmental benefits to recycling batteries?", answer: "Yes, recycling recovers valuable metals, reduces mining of virgin resources, prevents toxic chemical leaks, and reduces landfill waste. One recycled battery can power a recycling facility for months." },
  { question: "How much energy does battery recycling save?", answer: "Battery recycling can save up to 95% of the energy required to produce new batteries from virgin materials. This significantly reduces the carbon footprint of battery production." },
  { question: "What are the most toxic battery types?", answer: "Lead-acid batteries are highly toxic due to sulfuric acid and lead content. Lithium-ion batteries pose fire risks, while nickel-cadmium batteries contain carcinogenic cadmium." },
  { question: "Can battery recycling reduce mining impacts?", answer: "Absolutely. Recycling recovers cobalt, lithium, nickel, and other rare metals, reducing the need for environmentally destructive mining operations." },
  { question: "How does battery waste affect marine life?", answer: "Battery chemicals leach into waterways and bioaccumulate in fish and shellfish, affecting marine ecosystems and seafood safety for human consumption." },
  { question: "What's the environmental cost of improper battery disposal?", answer: "Improper disposal can contaminate hundreds of gallons of groundwater per battery, create long-term soil toxicity, and contribute to air pollution through incineration." },
  { question: "Are rechargeable batteries more environmentally friendly?", answer: "Yes, rechargeable batteries reduce waste compared to single-use batteries, but they still require proper recycling at end-of-life to prevent environmental contamination." },
  { question: "How long do batteries take to decompose?", answer: "Batteries don't biodegrade. Plastics may break down in centuries, but metals and chemicals remain toxic indefinitely, continuously leaching into the environment." },
  
